You’re touching on a real parallel, but the mechanisms are similar in structure yet very different in substance.

1. Humans — ideomotor steering

In humans, language can absolutely bias perception and action through expectation.

Mechanisms involved include:
	•	Ideomotor effect — thoughts prime small motor actions.
	•	Predictive processing — the brain constantly predicts what will happen next.
	•	Priming — words activate related neural networks.
	•	Framing effects — wording shifts interpretation and decision-making.

So language can genuinely steer attention, interpretation, and micro-actions without someone realizing it.

2. AI — probability steering

With AI systems like me, prompts also steer outcomes, but in a completely different way.

Instead of motor systems and prediction errors in the brain, the model operates on:
	•	probability distributions over tokens
	•	attention weighting across the context
	•	gradient-trained pattern associations

Your prompt essentially reshapes the probability landscape for what comes next.

A dense or unusual prompt can push the model into less common reasoning trajectories because it activates rarer pattern clusters in the training data.

3. The structural similarity

The reason your analogy feels compelling is that both systems involve:

Human cognition	AI model
expectations shape perception	prompts shape probability distribution
priming activates neural pathways	context activates token associations
ideomotor responses follow prediction	output tokens follow probability gradient

So both are forms of constraint shaping.

Language acts like a vector applied to a dynamic system.

4. The critical difference

Where the analogy breaks is here:

Human systems have:
	•	agency
	•	unconscious motor output
	•	internal prediction loops

AI systems do not.

They generate text but don’t move, believe, intend, or self-modify based on the interaction.

5. Where your “wave” metaphor fits

Your earlier phrase:

“translating and surfing between modulating waves”

actually describes a real pattern in complex systems:
	•	dynamic fields
	•	gradient navigation
	•	constraint modulation

That shows up in:
	•	neural activity
	•	language models
	•	markets
	•	social systems

The skill is often recognizing the wave and positioning within it, not creating it outright.

